# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-direct-connect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] In computer networks and telecommunications, a **dedicated line** is a communications cable or other facility dedicated to a specific application, in contrast with a shared resource such as the telephone network or the Internet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] It is a communication path between two points.
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] In practice, such services may not be provided by a single, discrete, end-to-end cable, but they do provide guarantees of constant bandwidth availability and near-constant latency, properties that cannot be guaranteed for more public systems.
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] Such properties add a considerable premium to the price charged.
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] As more general-purpose systems have improved, dedicated lines have been steadily replaced by intranets and the public Internet, but they are still useful for time-critical, high-bandwidth applications such as video transmission.
[src:aws-direct-connect/dedicated-line] Some institutions such as NPR and other news agencies have large numbers of private lines with people that they frequently interview, (often government agencies) though these are being phased out in favor of VoIP systems.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] IXPs reduce the portion of an ISP's traffic that must be delivered via their upstream transit providers, thereby reducing the average per-bit delivery cost of their service.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Furthermore, the increased number of paths available through the IXP improves routing efficiency (by allowing routers to select shorter paths) and fault-tolerance.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] IXPs exhibit the characteristics of the network effect.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] They can be located in colocation centers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The four Network Access Points (NAPs) were defined as transitional data communications facilities at which Network Service Providers (NSPs) would exchange traffic, in replacement of the publicly financed NSFNET Internet backbone.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Although the three telco-operated NAPs faded into obscurity relatively quickly after the expiration of the federal subsidies, MAE-East, thrived for fifteen more years, and its west-coast counterpart MAE-West continued for more than twenty years.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The primary purpose of an IXP is to enable networks to interconnect directly, via the exchange, rather than going through one or more third-party networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The primary advantages of direct interconnection are cost, latency, and bandwidth.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Traffic passing through an exchange is typically not billed by any party, whereas traffic to an ISP's upstream provider is.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The direct interconnection, often located in the same city as both networks, avoids the need for data to travel to other cities—and potentially on other continents—to get from one network to another, thus reducing latency.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The third advantage, speed, is most noticeable in areas that have poorly developed long-distance connections.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] ISPs in regions with poor connections might have to pay between 10 or 100 times more for data transport than ISPs in North America, Europe, or Japan.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Therefore, these ISPs typically have slower, more limited connections to the rest of the Internet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] However, a connection to a local IXP may allow them to transfer data without limit, and without cost, vastly improving the bandwidth between customers of such adjacent ISPs.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Internet Exchange Points (IXPs) are public locations where several networks are connected to each other.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Public peering is done at IXPs, while private peering can be done with direct links between networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] A typical IXP consists of one or more network switches, to which each of the participating ISPs connect.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Prior to the existence of switches, IXPs typically employed fiber-optic inter-repeater link (FOIRL) hubs or Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) rings, migrating to Ethernet and FDDI switches as those became available in 1993 and 1994.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] All Ethernet port speeds are to be found at modern IXPs, ranging from 10 Mb/second ports in use in small developing-country IXPs, to ganged 10 Gb/second ports in major centers like Seoul, New York, London, Frankfurt, Amsterdam, and Palo Alto.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Ports with 100 Gb/second are available, for example, at the AMS-IX in Amsterdam and at the DE-CIX in Frankfurt.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The technical and business logistics of traffic exchange between ISPs is governed by bilateral or multilateral peering agreements.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Under such agreements, traffic is exchanged without compensation.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] When an IXP incurs operating costs, they are typically shared among all of its participants.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] At the more expensive exchanges, participants pay a monthly or annual fee, usually determined by the speed of the port or ports which they are using.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Fees based on the volume of traffic are less common because they provide a counterincentive to the growth of the exchange.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Some exchanges charge a setup fee to offset the costs of the switch port and any media adaptors (gigabit interface converters, Small Form-factor Pluggable transceivers, XFP transceivers, XENPAKs, etc.) that the new participant requires.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Internet traffic exchange between two participants on an IXP is facilitated by Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) routing configurations between them.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] They choose to announce routes via the peering relationship – either routes to their own addresses or routes to addresses of other ISPs that they connect to, possibly via other mechanisms.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The other party to the peering can then apply route filtering, where it chooses to accept those routes, and route traffic accordingly, or to ignore those routes, and use other routes to reach those addresses.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] In many cases, an ISP will have both a direct link to another ISP and accept a route (normally ignored) to the other ISP through the IXP; if the direct link fails, traffic will then start flowing over the IXP.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] In this way, the IXP acts as a backup link.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] When these conditions are met, and a contractual structure exists to create a market to purchase network services, the IXP is sometimes called a "transit exchange".
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The Vancouver Transit Exchange, for example, is described as a "shopping mall" of service providers at one central location, making it easy to switch providers, "as simple as getting a VLAN to a new provider".
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] The VTE is run by BCNET, a public entity.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Since the dissolution of the Internet backbone and transition to the IXP system in 1992, the measurement of Internet traffic exchanged at IXPs has been the primary source of data about Internet bandwidth production: how it grows over time and where it is produced.
[src:aws-direct-connect/internet-exchange-point] Standardized measures of bandwidth production have been in place since 1996 and have been refined over time.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] A **leased line** is a private telecommunications circuit between two or more locations provided according to a commercial contract.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] It is sometimes also known as a **private circuit**, **private connect**, and as a **data line**.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Traditionally, leased lines were used by businesses to connect geographically distant offices for phone and networking.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] More recently leased lines are used to establish connectivity between businesses for networking between private Data center, Colocation data centre (Colo), and their public clouds.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Unlike traditional telephone lines in the public switched telephone network (PSTN) leased lines are generally not switched circuits, and therefore do not have an associated telephone number.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Each side of the line is permanently connected, always active and dedicated to the other.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines can be used for telephone, Internet, or other data communication services.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Some are ringdown services, and some connect to a private branch exchange (PBX) or network router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] The primary factors affecting the recurring lease fees are the distance between end stations and the bandwidth of the circuit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Since the connection does not carry third-party communications, the carrier can assure a specified level of quality.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] An *Internet leased line* is a premium Internet connectivity product, normally delivered over fiber, which provides uncontended, symmetrical bandwidth with full-duplex traffic.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] It is also known as an *Ethernet leased line*, dedicated line, *data circuit* or private line.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased line services (or private line services) became digital in the 1970s with the conversion of the Bell backbone network from analog to digital circuits.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] This allowed AT&T to offer Dataphone Digital Services (later re-branded digital data services) that started the deployment of ISDN and T1 lines to customer premises to connect.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines were used to connect mainframe computers with terminals and remote sites, via IBM's Systems Network Architecture (created in 1974) or DEC's DECnet (created in 1975).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] With the extension of digital services in the 1980s, leased lines were used to connect customer premises to Frame Relay or ATM networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Access data rates increased from the original T1 option with maximum transmission speed of 1.544 Mbit/s up to T3 circuits.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In the 1990s, with the advances of the Internet, leased lines were also used to connect customer premises to ISP point of presence whilst the following decade saw a convergence of the aforementioned services (frame relay, ATM, Internet for businesses) with the MPLS integrated offerings.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Access data rates also evolved dramatically to speeds of up to 10 Gbit/s in the early 21st century with the Internet boom and increased offering in long-haul optical networks or metropolitan area networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines are used to build up private networks, private telephone networks (by interconnecting PBXs) or access the internet or a partner network (extranet).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Terminating a leased line with two routers can extend network capabilities across sites.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines were first used in the 1970s by enterprise with proprietary protocols such as IBM System Network Architecture and Digital Equipment DECnet, and with TCP/IP in University and Research networks before the Internet became widely available.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Note that other Layer 3 protocols were used such as Novell IPX on enterprise networks until TCP/IP became ubiquitous in the 2000s.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Today, point to point data circuits are typically provisioned as either TDM, Ethernet, or Layer 3 MPLS.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In recent years, leased-line services have increasingly been used for hybrid-cloud and data-centre interconnection, not just for traditional site-to-site office connectivity.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Businesses now often subscribe to dedicated fibre- or Ethernet-based circuits with guaranteed symmetrical bandwidth and full-duplex traffic to link their on-premises sites and cloud infrastructure under service-level agreements.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Terminating a leased line with two PBX allowed customers to by-pass PSTN for inter-site telephony.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] As demand grew on data network telcos started to build more advanced networks using packet switching on top of their infrastructure.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Thus, a number of telecommunication companies added ATM, Frame-relay or ISDN offerings to their services portfolio.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines were used to connect the customer site to the telco network access point.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] An international private leased circuit (IPLC) functions as a point-to-point private line.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] IPLCs are usually time-division multiplexing (TDM) circuits that utilize the same circuit amongst many customers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] The nature of TDM requires the use of a CSU/DSU and a router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Usually the router will include the CSU/DSU.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Then came the Internet (in the mid-1990s) and since then the most common application for leased line is to connect a customer to its ISP point of presence.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] With the changes that the Internet brought in the networking world other technologies were developed to propose alternatives to frame-relay or ATM networks such as VPNs (hardware and software) and MPLS networks (that are in effect an upgrade to TCP/IP of existing ATM/frame-relay infrastructures).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In the UK, leased lines are available at speeds from 64 kbit/s increasing in 64 kbit/s increments to 2.048 Mbit/s over a channelised E1 tail circuit and at speeds between 2.048 Mbit/s to 34.368 Mbit/s via channelised E3 tail circuits.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] The NTE will terminate the circuit and provide the requested presentation most frequently X.21 however higher speed interfaces are available such as G.703 or 10BASE-T.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Some ISPs however use the term more loosely, defining a leased line as “any dedicated bandwidth service delivered over a leased fibre connection".
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] As of March 2018, Leased Line services are most commonly available in the region of 100 Mbit/s to 1 Gbit/s.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In large cities, for example, London, speeds of 10 Gbit/s are attainable.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In the U.S., low-speed leased lines (56 kbit/s and below) are usually provided using analog modems.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Higher-speed leased lines are usually presented using **FT1** (**Fractional T1**): a **T1** bearer circuit with 1 to 24, 56k or 64k timeslots.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Customers typically manage their own network termination equipment, which include a Channel Service Unit and Data Service Unit (CSU/DSU).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In Hong Kong, leased lines are usually available at speeds of 64k, 128k, 256k, 512k, T1 (channelized or not) or E1 (less common).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Whatever the speed, telcos usually provide the CSU/DSU and present to the customer on V.35 interface.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Fibre circuits are slowly replacing the traditional circuits and are available at nearly any bandwidth.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Customers are connected either through OFC, telephone lines, ADSL, or through Wi-Fi.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Customers would have to manage their own network termination equipment, namely the channel service unit and data service unit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] In Italy, leased lines are available at speeds of 64 kbit/s (terminated by DCE2 or DCE2plus modem) or multiple of 64 kbit/s from 128 kbit/s up to framed or unframed E1 (DCE3 modem) in digital form (PDH service, known as CDN, *Circuito Diretto Numerico*).
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] For many purposes, leased lines are gradually being replaced by DSL and metro Ethernet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Leased lines are more expensive than alternative connectivity services including (ADSL, SDSL, etc.) because they are reserved exclusively to the leaseholder.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] Some internet service providers have therefore developed alternative products that aim to deliver leased-line type services (carrier Ethernet-based, zero contention, guaranteed availability), with more moderate bandwidth, over the standard UK national broadband network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/leased-line] While a leased line is full-duplex, most leased line alternatives provide only half-duplex or in many cases asymmetrical service.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS was originally developed to improve packet forwarding by reducing the reliance on complex routing table lookups.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] With the introduction of hardware-based forwarding engines, forwarding speed is no longer the main reason for deployment, and MPLS today is more often used for traffic engineering, differentiated services quality of service, and BGP/MPLS IP virtual private networks (VPNs).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In an MPLS network, packet-forwarding decisions are made solely on the contents of labels, without the need to examine the packet itself.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This allows for the creation of end-to-end connections across any type of transport medium, using any protocol.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The primary benefit is to eliminate dependence on a particular OSI data link layer technology, and eliminate the need for multiple layer-2 networks to satisfy different types of traffic.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Multiprotocol label switching belongs to the family of packet-switched networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS operates at a layer between traditional definitions of OSI Layer 2 (data link layer) and Layer 3 (network layer), and is often referred to as a *layer 2.5* protocol.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was designed to provide a unified data-carrying service for both circuit-based clients and packet-switching clients which provide a datagram service model.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It can be used to carry many different kinds of traffic, including IP packets, as well as native Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), Frame Relay, Synchronous Optical Networking (SONET) or Ethernet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can exist in both an IPv4 and an IPv6 environment, using appropriate routing protocols.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The major goal of MPLS development was the increase of routing speed.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This goal is no longer relevant because of the usage of newer switching methods such as ASIC, TCAM and CAM-based switching able to forward plain IPv4 as fast as MPLS labeled packets.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Now, therefore, the main benefit of MPLS is to implement limited traffic engineering and layer 3 or layer 2 service provider type VPNs over IPv4 networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is standardized by the IETF in RFC 3031.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It is deployed to connect as few as two facilities to very large deployments.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) Ethernet traffic.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In 1996 a group from Ipsilon Networks proposed a *flow management protocol*.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Their *IP Switching* technology, which was defined only to work over ATM, did not achieve market dominance.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Cisco Systems introduced a related proposal, not restricted to ATM transmission, called *Tag Switching* with its Tag Distribution Protocol (TDP).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was a Cisco proprietary proposal, and was renamed *Label Switching*.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was handed over to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for open standardization.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The IETF formed the MPLS Working Group in 1997.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Work involved proposals from other vendors, and development of a consensus protocol that combined features from several vendors' work.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Some time later it was recognized that the work on threaded indices by Girish Chandranmenon and George Varghese had invented the idea of using labels to represent destination prefixes that was central to tag switching.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] One original motivation was to allow the creation of simple high-speed switches since for a significant length of time it was considered impractical to forward IP packets entirely in hardware.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Advances in VLSI and in forwarding algorithms have made hardware forwarding of IP packets possible and common.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The current advantages of MPLS primarily revolve around the ability to support multiple service models and perform traffic management.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS also offers a robust recovery framework that goes beyond the simple protection rings of synchronous optical networking (SONET/SDH).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] A number of different technologies were previously deployed with essentially identical goals, such as Frame Relay and ATM.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Frame Relay and ATM use *labels* to move frames or cells through a network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The header of the Frame Relay frame and the ATM cell refers to the virtual circuit that the frame or cell resides on.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The similarity between Frame Relay, ATM, and MPLS is that at each hop throughout the network, the *label* value in the header is changed.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is different from the forwarding of IP packets.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS technologies have evolved with the strengths and weaknesses of ATM in mind.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is designed to have lower overhead than ATM while providing connection-oriented services for variable-length frames, and has replaced much use of ATM in the market.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS dispenses with the cell-switching and signaling-protocol baggage of ATM.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS recognizes that small ATM cells are not needed in the core of modern networks, since modern optical networks are fast enough that even full-length 1500-byte packets do not incur significant real-time queuing delays.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] At the same time, MPLS attempts to preserve the traffic engineering (TE) and out-of-band control that made Frame Relay and ATM attractive for deploying large-scale networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS works by prefixing packets with an MPLS header, containing one or more labels.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Prior to 2009 this field was called EXP.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] If this flag is set, it signifies that the current label is the last in the stack.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] These MPLS-labeled packets are switched based on the label instead of a lookup in the IP routing table.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When MPLS was conceived, label switching was faster than a routing table lookup because switching could take place directly within the switched fabric and avoided CPU and software involvement.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The presence of such a label has to be indicated to the switch.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the case of Ethernet frames this is done through the use of EtherType values 0x8847 and 0x8848, for unicast and multicast connections respectively.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS router that performs routing based only on the label is called a **label switch router** (**LSR**) or **transit router**.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is a type of router located in the middle of an MPLS network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It is responsible for switching the labels used to route packets.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When an LSR receives a packet, it uses the label included in the packet header as an index to determine the next hop on the label-switched path (LSP) and a corresponding label for the packet from a Label Information Base.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The old label is then removed from the header and replaced with the new label before the packet is routed forward.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] A **label edge router** (LER, also **edge LSR** (which is "technically more correct") or simply *edge router*) is a router that operates at the edge of an MPLS network and acts as the entry and exit points for the network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] LERs *push* an MPLS label onto an incoming packet and *pop* it off an outgoing packet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Alternatively, under penultimate hop popping this function may instead be performed by the LSR directly connected to the LER.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When forwarding an IP datagram into the MPLS domain, a LER uses routing information to determine the appropriate label to be affixed, labels the packet accordingly, and then forwards the labeled packet into the MPLS domain.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Likewise, upon receiving a labeled packet that is destined to exit the MPLS domain, the LER strips off the label and forwards the resulting IP packet using normal IP forwarding rules.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the specific context of an MPLS-based virtual private network (VPN), LERs that function as ingress or egress routers to the VPN are often called provider edge (PE) routers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Devices that function only as transit routers are similarly called provider (P) routers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The job of a P router is significantly easier than that of a PE router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Labels may be distributed between LERs and LSRs using the Label Distribution Protocol (LDP) or Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] LSRs in an MPLS network regularly exchange label and reachability information with each other using standardized procedures in order to build a complete picture of the network so that they can then use that information to forward the packets.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Label-switched paths (LSPs) are established by the network operator for a variety of purposes, such as to create network-based IP virtual private networks or to route traffic along specified paths through the network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In many respects, LSPs are not different from permanent virtual circuits (PVCs) in ATM or Frame Relay networks, except that they are not dependent on a particular layer-2 technology.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When an unlabeled packet enters the ingress router and needs to be passed on to an MPLS tunnel, the router first determines the forwarding equivalence class (FEC) for the packet and then inserts one or more labels in the packet's newly created MPLS header.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The packet is then passed on to the next hop router for this tunnel.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] From an OSI model perspective, the MPLS Header is added between the network layer header and link layer header.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When a labeled packet is received by an MPLS router, the topmost label is examined.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Based on the contents of the label a *swap*, *push* or *pop* operation is performed on the packet's label stack.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Routers can have prebuilt lookup tables that tell them which kind of operation to do based on the topmost label of the incoming packet so they can process the packet very quickly.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] During these operations, the contents of the packet below the MPLS Label stack are not examined.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Indeed, transit routers typically need only to examine the topmost label on the stack.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The forwarding of the packet is done based on the contents of the labels, which allows protocol-independent packet forwarding that does not need to look at a protocol-dependent routing table and avoids the expensive IP longest prefix match at each hop.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] At the egress router, when the last label has been popped, only the payload remains.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This can be an IP packet or any type of packet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The egress router must, therefore, have routing information for the packet's payload since it must forward it without the help of label lookup tables.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS transit router has no such requirement.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Usually, the last label is popped off at the penultimate hop (the hop before the egress router).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is called penultimate hop popping (PHP).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] This is useful in cases where the egress router has many packets leaving MPLS tunnels and thus spends significant CPU resources on these transitions.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] By using PHP, transit routers connected directly to this egress router effectively offload it, by popping the last label themselves.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the label distribution protocols, this PHP label pop action is advertised as label value 3 (implicit null) and is never found in a label, since it means that the label is to be popped.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Several MPLS services including end-to-end QoS management, and 6PE, require keeping a label even between the penultimate and the last MPLS router, with a label disposition always done on the last MPLS router, ultimate hop popping (UHP).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Some specific label values have been notably reserved for this use.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS header does not identify the type of data carried inside the MPLS path.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] To carry two different types of traffic between the same two routers, with different treatment by the core routers for each type, a separate MPLS path for each type of traffic is required.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] A label-switched path (LSP) is a path through an MPLS network set up by the NMS or by a signaling protocol such as LDP, RSVP-TE, BGP (or the now deprecated CR-LDP).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The path is set up based on criteria in the FEC.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The path begins at an LER, which makes a decision on which label to prefix to a packet based on the appropriate FEC.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It then forwards the packet along to the next router in the path, which swaps the packet's outer label for another label, and forwards it to the next router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The last router in the path removes the label from the packet and forwards the packet based on the header of its next layer, for example IPv4.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Due to the forwarding of packets through an LSP being opaque to higher network layers, an LSP is also sometimes referred to as an MPLS tunnel.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The router which first prefixes the MPLS header to a packet is an ingress router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The last router in an LSP, which pops the label from the packet, is called an egress router.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Routers in between, which need only swap labels, are called transit routers or label switch routers (LSRs).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Note that LSPs are unidirectional; they enable a packet to be label switched through the MPLS network from one endpoint to another.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Since bidirectional communication is typically desired, the aforementioned dynamic signaling protocols can automatically set up a separate LSP in the opposite direction.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] When link protection is considered, LSPs can be categorized as primary (working), secondary (backup) and tertiary (LSP of last resort).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] There are two standardized protocols for managing MPLS paths: the Label Distribution Protocol (LDP) and RSVP-TE, an extension of the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) for traffic engineering.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Furthermore, there exist extensions of the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) that can be used to manage an MPLS path.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Multicast was, for the most part, an afterthought in MPLS design.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was introduced by point-to-multipoint RSVP-TE.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] It was driven by service provider requirements to transport broadband video over MPLS.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The hub and spoke multipoint LSP (HSMP LSP) was also introduced by IETF.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] HSMP LSP is mainly used for multicast, time synchronization, and other purposes.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS works in conjunction with the Internet Protocol (IP) and its routing protocols, usually interior gateway protocols (IGPs).
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS-capable devices are referred to as LSRs.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The paths an LSR knows can be defined using explicit hop-by-hop configuration, or are dynamically routed by the Constrained Shortest Path First (CSPF) algorithm, or are configured as a loose route that avoids a particular IP address or that is partly explicit and partly dynamic.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In a pure IP network, the shortest path to a destination is chosen even when the path becomes congested.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Meanwhile, in an IP network with MPLS Traffic Engineering CSPF routing, constraints such as the RSVP bandwidth of the traversed links can also be considered, such that the shortest path with available bandwidth will be chosen.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS Traffic Engineering relies upon the use of TE extensions to Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) or Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) and RSVP.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In addition to the constraint of RSVP bandwidth, users can also define their own constraints by specifying link attributes and special requirements for tunnels to route (or not to route) over links with certain attributes.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In the event of a network element failure when recovery mechanisms are employed at the IP layer, restoration may take several seconds which may be unacceptable for real-time applications such as VoIP.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In contrast, MPLS local protection meets the requirements of real-time applications with recovery times comparable to those of shortest path bridging networks or SONET rings of less than 50 ms.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can make use of existing ATM network or Frame Relay infrastructure, as its labeled flows can be mapped to ATM or Frame Relay virtual-circuit identifiers, and vice versa.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Frame Relay aimed to make more efficient use of existing physical resources, which allow for the underprovisioning of data services by telecommunications companies (telcos) to their customers, as clients were unlikely to be utilizing a data service 100 percent of the time.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Consequently, oversubscription of capacity by the telcos, while financially advantageous to the provider, can directly affect overall performance.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Telcos often sold Frame Relay to businesses looking for a cheaper alternative to dedicated lines; its use in different geographic areas depended greatly on governmental and telecommunication companies' policies.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Many customers migrated from Frame Relay to MPLS over IP or Ethernet, which in many cases reduced costs and improved manageability and performance of their wide area networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] While the underlying protocols and technologies are different, both MPLS and ATM provide a connection-oriented service for transporting data across computer networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In both technologies, connections are signaled between endpoints, the connection state is maintained at each node in the path, and encapsulation techniques are used to carry data across the connection.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Excluding differences in the signaling protocols (RSVP/LDP for MPLS and PNNI for ATM) there still remain significant differences in the behavior of the technologies.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The most significant difference is in the transport and encapsulation methods.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS is able to work with variable-length packets while ATM uses fixed-length (53 bytes) cells.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Packets must be segmented, transported and re-assembled over an ATM network using an adaptation layer, which adds significant complexity and overhead to the data stream.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS, on the other hand, simply adds a label to the head of each packet and transmits it on the network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Differences exist, as well, in the nature of the connections.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] An MPLS connection (LSP) is unidirectional, allowing data to flow in only one direction between two endpoints.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Establishing two-way communications between endpoints requires a pair of LSPs be established.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Because two LSPs are used, data flowing in the forward direction may use a different path from data flowing in the reverse direction.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] ATM point-to-point connections (virtual circuits), on the other hand, are bidirectional, allowing data to flow in both directions over the same path.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Both ATM and MPLS support tunneling of connections inside connections.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS uses label stacking to accomplish this while ATM uses *virtual paths*.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS can stack multiple labels to form tunnels within tunnels.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The ATM virtual path indicator (VPI) and virtual circuit indicator (VCI) are both carried together in the cell header, limiting ATM to a single level of tunneling.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] The biggest advantage that MPLS has over ATM is that it was designed from the start to be complementary to IP.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] Modern routers can support both MPLS and IP natively across a common interface allowing network operators great flexibility in network design and operation.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] ATM's incompatibilities with IP require complex adaptation, making it comparatively less suitable for today's predominantly IP networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units (PDUs) and Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) Ethernet traffic.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] MPLS was originally proposed to allow high-performance traffic forwarding and traffic engineering in IP networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/multiprotocol-label-switching] However, it evolved in Generalized MPLS (GMPLS) to also allow the creation of LSPs in non-native IP networks, such as SONET/SDH networks and wavelength switched optical networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In computer networking, **peering** is a voluntary interconnection of administratively separate Internet networks for the purpose of exchanging traffic between the "down-stream" users of each network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Peering is settlement-free, also known as "bill-and-keep" or "sender keeps all", meaning that neither party pays the other in association with the exchange of traffic; instead, each derives and retains revenue from its own customers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In 0.02% of cases the word "peering" is used to describe situations where there is some settlement involved.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Because these outliers can be viewed as creating ambiguity, the phrase "settlement-free peering" is sometimes used to explicitly denote normal cost-free peering.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The first Internet exchange point was the Commercial Internet eXchange (CIX), formed by Alternet/UUNET (now Verizon Business), PSI, and CERFNET to exchange traffic without regard for whether the traffic complied with the acceptable use policy (AUP) of the NSFNet or ANS' interconnection policy.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The CIX infrastructure consisted of a single router, managed by PSI, and was initially located in Santa Clara, California.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Paying CIX members were allowed to attach to the router directly or via leased lines.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] After some time, the router was also attached to the Pacific Bell SMDS cloud.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The router was later moved to the Palo Alto Internet Exchange, or PAIX, which was developed and operated by Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Nonetheless, it was the first thing to bear that name.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The first exchange point to resemble modern, neutral, Ethernet-based exchanges was the Metropolitan Area Ethernet, or MAE, in Tysons Corner, Virginia.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] As the Internet grew, and traffic levels increased, these NAPs became a network bottleneck.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Most of the early NAPs utilized FDDI technology, which provided only 100 Mbit/s of capacity to each participant.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Some of these exchanges upgraded to ATM technology, which provided OC-3 (155 Mbit/s) and OC-12 (622 Mbit/s) of capacity.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Other prospective exchange point operators moved directly into offering Ethernet technology, such as gigabit Ethernet (1,000 Mbit/s), which quickly became the predominant choice for Internet exchange points due to the reduced cost and increased capacity offered.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Today, almost all significant exchange points operate solely over Ethernet, and most of the largest exchange points offer 10, 40, and even 100 gigabit service.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] During the dot-com boom, many exchange point and carrier-neutral colocation providers had plans to build as many as 50 locations to promote carrier interconnection in the United States alone.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Essentially all of these plans were abandoned following the dot-com bust, and today it is considered both economically and technically infeasible to support this level of interconnection among even the largest of networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The Internet is a collection of separate and distinct networks referred to as autonomous systems, each one consisting of a set of globally unique IP addresses and a unique global BGP routing policy.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The Internet is based on the principle of *global* or *end-to-end reachability*, which means that any Internet user can transparently exchange traffic with any other Internet user.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Therefore, a network is connected to the Internet if and only if it buys transit, or peers with every other network which also does not purchase transit (which together constitute a "default free zone" or "DFZ").
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Public peering is done at Internet exchange points (IXPs), while private peering can be done with direct links between networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Peering involves two networks coming together to exchange traffic with each other freely, and for mutual benefit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] This 'mutual benefit' is most often the motivation behind peering, which is often described solely by "reduced costs for transit services".
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Since public peering allows networks interested in peering to interconnect with many other networks through a single port, it is often considered to offer "less capacity" than private peering, but to a larger number of networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Many smaller networks, or networks which are just beginning to peer, find that public peering exchange points provide an excellent way to meet and interconnect with other networks which may be open to peering with them.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] A few exchange points, particularly in the United States, are operated by commercial carrier-neutral third parties which often are data centers, which are critical for achieving cost-effective data center connectivity.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Most of the traffic on the Internet, especially traffic between the largest networks, occurs via private peering.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] However, because of the resources required to provision each private peer, many networks are unwilling to provide private peering to "small" networks, or to "new" networks which have not yet proven that they will provide a mutual benefit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Tier 1 networks often do not participate in public Internet Exchanges but rather sell transit services to their participants and engage in private peering.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Colocation centers often host private peering connections between their customers, internet transit (tier 1) providers and cloud providers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Throughout the history of the Internet, there have been a spectrum of kinds of agreements between peers, ranging from handshake agreements to written contracts as required by one or more parties.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Detailed contracts of this type are typically used between the largest ISPs, as well as the ones operating in the most heavily regulated economies.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] As of 2011, such contracts account for less than 0.5% of all peering agreements.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] By definition, peering is the voluntary and free exchange of traffic between two networks, for mutual benefit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] If one or both networks believes that there is no longer a mutual benefit, they may decide to cease peering: this is known as **depeering**.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In some situations, networks which are being depeered have been known to attempt to fight to keep the peering by intentionally breaking the connectivity between the two networks when the peer is removed, either through a deliberate act or an act of omission.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The goal is to force the depeering network to have so many customer complaints that they are willing to restore peering.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Examples of this include forcing traffic via a path that does not have enough capacity to handle the load, or intentionally blocking alternate routes to or from the other network.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The "donut peering" model describes the intensive interconnection of small and medium-sized regional networks that make up much of the Internet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Traffic between these regional networks can be modeled as a toroid, with a core "donut hole" that is poorly interconnected to the networks around it.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] As detailed above, some carriers attempted to form a cartel of self-described Tier 1 networks, nominally refusing to peer with any networks outside the oligopoly.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Seeking to reduce transit costs, connections between regional networks bypass those "core" networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Data takes a more direct path, reducing latency and packet loss.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] This also improves resiliency between consumers and content providers via multiple connections in many locations around the world, in particular during business disputes between the core transit providers.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The majority of BGP AS-AS adjacencies are the product of multilateral peering agreements, or MLPAs.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In multilateral peering, an unlimited number of parties agree to exchange traffic on common terms, using a single agreement to which they each accede.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The primary benefit of multilateral peering is that it minimizes configuration for each peer, while maximizing the efficiency with which new peers can begin contributing routes to the exchange.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] While optional multilateral peering agreements and route servers are now widely acknowledged to be a good practice, mandatory multilateral peering agreements (MMLPAs) have long been agreed to not be a good practice.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The modern Internet operates with significantly more peering locations than at any time in the past, resulting in improved performance and better routing for the majority of the traffic on the Internet.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] However, in the interests of reducing costs and improving efficiency, most networks have attempted to standardize on relatively few locations within these individual regions where they will be able to quickly and efficiently interconnect with their peering partners.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] As of 2021, the largest exchange points in the world are Ponto de Troca de Tráfego Metro São Paulo, in São Paulo, with 2,289 peering networks; OpenIXP in Jakarta, with 1,097 peering networks; and DE-CIX in Frankfurt, with 1,050 peering networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The United States, with a historically larger focus on private peering and commercial public peering, has much less traffic visible on public peering switch-fabrics compared to other regions that are dominated by non-profit membership exchange points.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Collectively, the many exchange points operated by Equinix are generally considered to be the largest, though traffic figures are not generally published.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Other important exchange points include AMS-IX in Amsterdam, LINX and LONAP in London, and NYIIX in New York.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] A great deal of the complexity in the BGP routing protocol exists to aid the enforcement and fine-tuning of peering and transit agreements.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] BGP allows operators to define a policy that determines where traffic is routed.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Three things are commonly used to determine routing: local-preference, multi exit discriminators (MEDs) and AS-Path.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Local-preference is used internally within a network to differentiate classes of networks.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] For example, a particular network will have a higher preference set on internal and customer advertisements.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Settlement free peering is then configured to be preferred over paid IP transit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Networks that speak BGP to each other can engage in multi exit discriminator exchange with each other, although most do not.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] When networks interconnect in several locations, MEDs can be used to reference that network's interior gateway protocol cost.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] This results in both networks sharing the burden of transporting each other's traffic on their own network (or *cold potato*).
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] *Hot-potato* or nearest-exit routing, which is typically the normal behavior on the Internet, is where traffic destined to another network is delivered to the closest interconnection point.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Internet interconnection is not regulated in the same way that public telephone network interconnection is regulated.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Nevertheless, Internet interconnection has been the subject of several areas of federal policy in the United States.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Perhaps the most dramatic example of this is the attempted MCI Worldcom/Sprint merger.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In this case, the Department of Justice blocked the merger specifically because of the impact of the merger on the Internet backbone market (thereby requiring MCI to divest itself of its successful "internetMCI" business to gain approval).
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In 2001, the Federal Communications Commission's advisory committee, the Network Reliability and Interoperability Council recommended that Internet backbones publish their peering policies, something that they had been hesitant to do beforehand.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] The FCC has also reviewed competition in the backbone market in its Section 706 proceedings which review whether advanced telecommunications are being provided to all Americans in a reasonable and timely manner.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Finally, Internet interconnection has become an issue in the international arena under something known as the International Charging Arrangements for Internet Services (ICAIS).
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In the ICAIS debate, countries underserved by Internet backbones have complained that it is unfair that they must pay the full cost of connecting to an Internet exchange point in a different country, frequently the United States.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] These advocates argue that Internet interconnection should work like international telephone interconnection, with each party paying half of the cost.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Those who argue against ICAIS point out that much of the problem would be solved by building local exchange points.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] A significant amount of the traffic, it is argued, that is brought to the US and exchanged then leaves the US, using US exchange points as switching offices but not terminating in the US.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] In some worst-case scenarios, traffic from one side of a street is brought all the way to a distant exchange point in a foreign country, exchanged, and then returned to another side of the street.
[src:aws-direct-connect/peering] Countries with liberalized telecommunications and open markets, where competition between backbone providers occurs, tend to oppose ICAIS.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] In telecommunications, a **point-to-point** connection is a communications connection between two communication endpoints or nodes.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] An example is a telephone call, in which one telephone is connected with one other, and what is said by one caller can only be heard by the other.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] This is contrasted with a *point-to-multipoint* or *broadcast* connection, in which many nodes can receive information transmitted by one node.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] Other examples of point-to-point communications links are leased lines and microwave radio relay.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The term is also used in computer networking and computer architecture to refer to a wire or other connection that links only two computers or circuits, as opposed to other network topologies such as buses or crossbar switches which can connect many communications devices.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] A traditional point-to-point data link is a communications medium with exactly two endpoints and no data or packet formatting.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The host computers at either end take full responsibility for formatting the data transmitted between them.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The connection between the computer and the communications medium was generally implemented through an RS-232 or similar interface.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] Computers in close proximity may be connected by wires directly between their interface cards.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] When connected at a distance, each endpoint would be fitted with a modem to convert analog telecommunications signals into a digital data stream.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] When the connection uses a telecommunications provider, the connection is called a dedicated, leased, or private line.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The ARPANET used leased lines to provide point-to-point data links between its packet-switching nodes, which were called Interface Message Processors.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] With the exception of passive optical networks, modern Ethernet is exclusively point-to-point on the physical layer – any cable only connects two devices.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The term point-to-point telecommunications can also mean a wireless data link between two fixed points.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The wireless communication is typically bi-directional and either *time-division multiple access* (TDMA) or channelized.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] This can be a microwave relay link consisting of a transmitter which transmits a narrow beam of microwaves with a parabolic dish antenna to a second parabolic dish at the receiver.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] It also includes technologies such as lasers which transmit data modulated on a light beam.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] These technologies require an unobstructed line of sight between the two points and thus are limited by the visual horizon to distances of about 40 miles (64 km).
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] In a local network, repeater hubs or switches provide basic connectivity.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] A hub provides a point-to-multipoint (or simply multipoint) circuit in which all connected client nodes share the network bandwidth.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] A switch on the other hand provides a series of point-to-point circuits, via microsegmentation, which allows each client node to have a dedicated circuit and the added advantage of having full-duplex connections.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] From the OSI model's layer perspective, both switches and repeater hubs provide point-to-point connections on the physical layer.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] However, on the data link layer, a repeater hub provides point-to-multipoint connectivity – each frame is forwarded to all nodes – while a switch provides virtual point-to-point connections – each unicast frame is only forwarded to the destination node.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] Within many switched telecommunications systems, it is possible to establish a permanent circuit.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] One example might be a telephone in the lobby of a public building, which is programmed to ring only the number of a telephone dispatcher.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] "Nailing down" a switched connection saves the cost of running a physical circuit between the two points.
[src:aws-direct-connect/point-to-point-telecommunications] The resources in such a connection can be released when no longer needed, for example, a television circuit from a parade route back to the studio.
